- Preferences: close, natural midrange vocals and vocal intimacy; inventive multitracked/ensemble harmonies and arrangements that serve harmony first; restrained electric/acoustic guitar with tasteful organ color; low‑compression/tape‑like punch and preserved headroom; clear instrument separation and preserved quiet moments; warm AOR/folk‑rock mixes, concise song pacing, groove and melody/front‑and‑center sequencing.
- Dislikes: slick 1980s gloss and synth‑centric timbres; synthetic percussion; heavy compression/over‑limiting; oversized artificial reverb; piano‑forward cinematic mixes that sideline ensemble vocals; showy or sprawling solo/prog detours; murky lo‑fi that sacrifices clarity.
Evaluation and choice
- Why the Curated Paul Simon anthology matches: The anthology is described with crystal‑clear, front‑of‑mix storytelling vocals, low/modest compression, minimal reverb, tasteful harmonies, sparse guitar/piano interplay, preserved quiet moments, and clean instrumental separation. Those are direct matches to my core priorities: natural midrange vocals and vocal intimacy (front‑of‑mix storytelling), minimal processing and preserved headroom (low/modest compression, minimal reverb), arrangements that foreground intelligible lyrics and harmonies rather than flashy soloing (sparse interplay and tasteful harmonies), and preservation of quiet dynamics and transient snap. The anthology’s focus on conversational detail and immediacy aligns with my taste for close, analogue‑feeling midrange and melody‑first sequencing. Importantly, nothing in the anthology’s description suggests synth‑centric timbres, oversized reverb, or heavy limiting — all things I dislike.
- Why the Remastered Vault is less suitable: Although the Vault keeps dynamic punch and stacked harmonies and avoids heavy over‑limiting, it is characterized as a glossy arena AOR package with bright controlled synths, punchy tight drums, snapping bass, and layered full‑length solos up front. Those features conflict with several stated dislikes and lower‑priority elements for me: the “glossy arena” aesthetic and bright synths lean toward the slick 1980s gloss and synth‑centric timbres I said I dislike; the emphasis on full‑length solos and arena immediacy works against my preference for harmony‑first arrangements and concise single‑ready pacing; punchy arena drums and heavy upfront production can also compromise the intimate, preserved headroom and natural midrange vocal presence I favor even if this particular remaster avoids over‑limiting. In short, the Vault’s strengths are tailored to arena/AOR listeners, not to someone who prioritizes close, natural vocals, quiet moments, and restrained guitar/ensemble balance.
Conclusion
Given the direct alignment of the Paul Simon anthology’s clear, front‑of‑mix vocals, minimal processing, tasteful harmonic treatment, preserved quiet moments and separation with my stated preferences — and the Remastered Vault’s arena gloss, synth presence, and showy soloing that contradict core dislikes — the Curated Paul Simon anthology is the better fit for my tastes.

