- Dislikes I stated: gritty lead vocals or sparse tracking pushed forward; heavy over‑limiting; oversized artificial reverb or crowd ambience; piano‑forward cinematic mixes; synth washes that bury vocals; muddy lo‑fi production; sprawling showy solos/prog detours; and arena/AOR treatments (gated‑drum punch, wide arena sheen) that dilute vocal intimacy.
2) Evaluation of the two candidates against those criteria
- Tumbleweed Connection: preserves tape transients and generous headroom (matches my desire for gentle tape saturation and natural dynamics); intimate close‑mic lead vocals with warm, tactile midrange (direct match to my midrange‑forward vocal preference); rich harmonies and revealing piano/cymbal shimmer (supports my craving for multitracked harmonies and tasteful acoustic keys without dominating the mix); prominent acoustic guitar, pedal steel and upright bass weight indicate an ensemble‑first arrangement and restrained low end rather than arena low‑end thump; spacious but tactile stereo imaging and tactile LP sequencing align with my preference for roominess that remains focused and concise sequencing/flow. Crucially, there is no mention of gated drums, arena sheen, or sprawling solos that would contradict my dislikes.
